Signal 1: CUI overlap (weight = 0.40)
  Exact set intersection: query_cuis ∩ chunk_cuis.
  Then hierarchy subsumption: for each unmatched query CUI,
  check if it appears in the UMLS ancestors of any chunk CUI.

  Step 1 — Exact match:
    C0231749 (Knee pain) in chunk?     NO
    C0003864 (Arthritis) in chunk?     NO
    C0087111 (Therapeutic) in chunk?   NO
    Exact overlap = 0

  Step 2 — Ancestor match:
    Walk UP from each chunk CUI and check if any query CUI appears.

    Query CUI: C0231749 (Knee pain)
      ancestors(C0582801 Left knee pain) = {C0231749, C0030193, ...}
      C0231749 FOUND → HIT
      Knee pain IS the parent of Left knee pain.

    Query CUI: C0003864 (Arthritis)
      ancestors(C0003873 RA) = {C0003864, C0022408, ...}
      C0003864 FOUND → HIT
      Arthritis IS the parent of RA.

    Query CUI: C0087111 (Therapeutic)
      No chunk CUI has C0087111 in its ancestors.
      → MISS

    Total: 2 out of 3 query CUIs matched.
    cui_overlap_ratio = 2/3 = 0.667

  This is the most trusted signal. Weight = 0.40.

  Strength: precise. C0231749 matches C0582801 because there is
            an actual parent-child link in the UMLS graph.
            Left knee ≠ right knee. RA ≠ OA. No confusion.
  Weakness: misses synonyms with different CUI codes.
            If the query uses a CUI that has no hierarchy
            link to any chunk CUI, this signal returns 0
            even if they mean the same thing.


Signal 2: Vector similarity (weight = 0.30)
  Cosine similarity between query centroid and chunk centroid.
  Both are 768-dim vectors, L2-normalized, so cosine = dot product.

  Query centroid:
    mean([emb(C0231749), emb(C0003864), emb(C0087111)]) → normalize
    = [0.24, -0.09, 0.45, 0.32, ...]

  Chunk centroid (precomputed at indexing time):
    mean([emb(C0582801), emb(C0003873), ..., emb(C0018099)]) → normalize
    = [0.18, 0.07, 0.33, 0.28, ...]

  dot(query_centroid, chunk_centroid) = 0.72

  vector_sim = 0.72

  One number. One dot product. O(1) per chunk.

  Strength: catches semantic similarity beyond CUI codes.
            "Sepsis" and "Septic shock" have different CUI codes
            and may not be parent-child, but their embeddings
            are 0.89 similar. This signal catches that.
  Weakness: cannot distinguish laterality.
            "OA left knee" and "OA right knee" have embeddings
            that are 0.95 similar. Vector says "match."
            But clinically they're different joints.
            That's why Signal 1 (CUI overlap) has higher weight —
            it catches left ≠ right because different CUI codes.


Signal 3: Lin similarity via MICA (weight = 0.30)
  For each query CUI, find its best Lin match among all chunk CUIs.
  Then average across all query CUIs. (Best Match Average)

  Lin formula: Lin(c1, c2) = 2 × IC(MICA) / (IC(c1) + IC(c2))

  MICA = Most Informative Common Ancestor.
  Walk UP from both CUIs, find shared ancestors,
  pick the one with highest IC.

  Query CUI: C0231749 (Knee pain, IC=12.1)
    vs C0582801 (Left knee pain, IC=14.6):
      ancestors(C0231749) = {C0030193 Pain, ...}
      ancestors(C0582801) = {C0231749 Knee pain, C0030193 Pain, ...}
      Shared: {C0231749 Knee pain (IC=12.1), C0030193 Pain (IC=4.2)}
      MICA = C0231749 (IC=12.1, highest)
      Lin = 2 × 12.1 / (12.1 + 14.6) = 24.2 / 26.7 = 0.906

    vs C0003873 (RA, IC=14.6):
      Shared ancestors: {C0030193 Pain? NO. Different branch.}
      MICA IC < 2.0 → no meaningful common ancestor
      Lin = 0.0

    Best match for C0231749 = 0.906 (via C0582801)

  Query CUI: C0003864 (Arthritis, IC=8.4)
    vs C0003873 (RA, IC=14.6):
      MICA = C0003864 Arthritis (IC=8.4)
      Lin = 2 × 8.4 / (8.4 + 14.6) = 16.8 / 23.0 = 0.730

    vs C0409959 (OA left knee, IC=14.65):
      MICA = C0003864 Arthritis (IC=8.4)
      Lin = 2 × 8.4 / (8.4 + 14.65) = 16.8 / 23.05 = 0.729

    Best match for C0003864 = 0.730 (via C0003873)

  Query CUI: C0087111 (Therapeutic, IC=6.5)
    No chunk CUI shares a meaningful ancestor (MICA IC < 2.0)
    Best match = 0.0

  Lin average = (0.906 + 0.730 + 0.0) / 3 = 0.545

  Strength: uses the hierarchy quantitatively.
            Signal 1 says "Arthritis matches RA" (yes/no).
            Signal 3 says "HOW WELL does Arthritis match RA?"
            Lin=0.730 means strong match. Lin=0.3 means weak.
            This ranks chunks by match quality, not just existence.
  Weakness: IC values are flat for leaf nodes (~14.6).
            Two leaves with the same parent get Lin ≈ 0.6
            regardless of how different they actually are.
            That's why embedding similarity (Signal 2) helps —
            it breaks the tie.
